# SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

In the context of **PCCPT302 – Microcontrollers and Embedded Systems (KTU 2024 Scheme)**, **Sample Code** refers to the canonical, reference C/Assembly programs used to demonstrate **GPIO (General Purpose Input/Output) interfacing**, **peripheral configuration**, and **real-world device actuation** using a target microcontroller (typically the **Intel 8051 family** or the **ARM7 / LPC2148** family depending on the elective track).

The set of sample programs covered in this module is the practical bridge between abstract register-level theory and the embedded industry workflow. They include:

1. **LED Interfacing** – Output device driving.
2. **Switch/Button Interfacing** – Digital input sensing (polling / interrupt).
3. **DC Motor Control** – Unidirectional/bidirectional speed control via **PWM (Pulse Width Modulation)**.
4. **Stepper Motor Control** – Precise angular positioning using excitation sequences.
5. **Temperature Monitoring System** – Analog acquisition through **ADC** with **LM35** sensor.
6. **Seven Segment Display Interfacing** – Numeric output visualization.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Highlight:** The Board expects students to be fluent in *register-level programming* (SFR manipulation) for 8051 and *CMSIS/HAL/Library-based* programming for LPC2148. Memorizing ready-made code is **not** sufficient; you must be able to **derive the control logic** and **modify the code** for unseen hardware variants — a frequently tested skill.

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

Imagine you are the **brain of a tiny robot**. You cannot shout, you cannot gesture — you can only send **precise electrical pulses** through specific wires (pins). Each wire has a name (P1.0, P0.3, P2.7 …) and a purpose.

- **LED code** = teaching the brain how to *turn on a light* (output LOW or HIGH, 0 V or 5 V).
- **Switch code** = teaching the brain to *listen* for a button press (read whether a pin is 0 or 1).
- **DC Motor code** = teaching the brain to *push a cart harder or softer* (PWM duty cycle).
- **Stepper Motor code** = teaching the brain to *rotate a clock hand in exact 1.8° increments*.
- **LM35 code** = teaching the brain to *take a patient's temperature* and convert an analog voltage to a digital number.
- **Seven Segment code** = teaching the brain to *display a digit* on a numeric screen.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The Core Abstraction:** Every embedded system is fundamentally about three operations — **Read** (input pin / ADC), **Process** (CPU + memory), and **Write** (output pin / PWM / display). All six sample programs in this module are variations of this same Read–Process–Write pipeline.

---

## 1.3 Physical Constants, Standard Metrics & Reference Values

| Parameter | Value | Unit | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| **8051 Clock (f<sub>OSC</sub>)** | **11.0592 MHz** (canonical) or 12 MHz | MHz | 11.0592 MHz yields exact 9600 baud for UART |
| **Logic HIGH (8051)** | **5 V** nominal (3.3 V on LPC2148) | V | TTL level |
| **Logic LOW (8051)** | **0 V** | V | — |
| **LM35 Sensitivity** | **10 mV / °C** | mV/°C | Linear, 0 °C → 0 V, 150 °C → 1.5 V |
| **LM35 Operating Range** | **−55 °C to +150 °C** | °C | Industrial grade |
| **ADC Reference Voltage (V<sub>REF</sub>)** | **+5.000 V** (typical) | V | LPC2148 has 3.3 V internal V<sub>REF</sub> |
| **ADC Resolution (8-bit)** | **256 levels** | discrete steps | Step size = V<sub>REF</sub>/256 |
| **ADC Resolution (10-bit LPC2148)** | **1024 levels** | discrete steps | Step size = V<sub>REF</sub>/1024 |
| **Stepper Motor Step Angle** | **1.8°** (typical 200-step) | degrees | Full-step, 200 steps/revolution |
| **Stepper Motor Half-Step** | **0.9°** (400 steps/revolution) | degrees | Half-step excitation |
| **PWM Frequency (LPC2148)** | Configurable, typically **1 kHz** | Hz | For DC motor: 1–25 kHz |
| **Human Eye Flicker Threshold** | **> 100 Hz** | Hz | Seven segment multiplex > 100 Hz |

