# SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Underlying Operational Principles — Bulleted Logic Breakdown

### 2.1.1 LED Interfacing
- **Why an LED needs a current-limiting resistor:** An LED is a non-ohmic diode. Without a series resistor R, current would exceed safe limits (I<sub>F</sub> ≈ 20 mA for a standard red LED).
- **Voltage drop across LED (V<sub>F</sub>):** Red ≈ **1.8 V**, Green ≈ **2.0 V**, Blue/White ≈ **3.2 V**.
- **Microcontroller pin drive capability:** 8051 standard port pin sinks/source ≈ **10–20 mA**; the entire 8051 port is limited to **≈ 60–80 mA** total — a critical limitation.

> [!NOTE]
> **Sink vs Source:** 8051 ports can **sink** more current (≈ 20 mA per pin) than they can **source** (≈ 3.5 mA). This is why LEDs in classic 8051 boards are wired with the **cathode to the MCU pin** and **anode to Vcc through R** — the pin pulls LOW to light the LED.

### 2.1.2 Switch / Button Interfacing
- **Active-LOW vs Active-HIGH:** Pull-up (or pull-down) resistors define the default logic level when the button is unpressed.
- **Switch bouncing:** Mechanical contacts bounce for **5–20 ms**. A software **debounce delay (≈ 10–50 ms)** is mandatory.
- **Polling vs Interrupt:**
  - *Polling* — CPU continuously checks pin; simpler but wastes cycles.
  - *Interrupt-driven* — CPU sleeps or does other work; EXTI flag triggers ISR.

### 2.1.3 DC Motor Control via PWM
- **Why PWM, not variable DC?** Transistors / H-bridges are most efficient when **fully ON** or **fully OFF**. PWM mimics an analog average by varying the duty cycle.
- **Average voltage delivered to motor:**

$$\boxed{V_{avg} = D \cdot V_{supply}}$$

where $D$ is the duty cycle (0 ≤ D ≤ 1).

- **H-Bridge (L293D / L298):** Enables bidirectional control by steering current through the motor in two directions using 4 switches arranged in an "H" topology.
- **Enable pin (EN1, EN2) of L293D** is fed the PWM signal for speed control; the input pins (IN1, IN2) decide direction.

### 2.1.4 Stepper Motor Control
- **Stepper motor types:** Unipolar (5/6 wire) and Bipolar (4 wire).
- **Full-step excitation sequence (4-step, unipolar):**

| Step | A | B | C | D |
|------|---|---|---|---|
| 1    | 1 | 0 | 0 | 0 |
| 2    | 0 | 1 | 0 | 0 |
| 3    | 0 | 0 | 1 | 0 |
| 4    | 0 | 0 | 0 | 1 |

- **Half-step sequence (8-step):** Interleaves the above with two-coil ON states for finer resolution.
- **Step angle relationship:**

$$\boxed{\theta_{step} = \frac{360°}{N_{steps/rev}}}$$

### 2.1.5 LM35 + ADC Temperature Monitoring
- **LM35 output voltage equation:**

$$V_{out} = 10\,\text{mV/°C} \cdot T(°C)$$

- **For 8-bit ADC with V<sub>REF</sub> = 5 V:**

$$T(°C) = \frac{ADC_{value} \times V_{REF}}{256 \times 10\,\text{mV}} = \frac{ADC_{value} \times 5}{2.56}$$

- **For 10-bit ADC (LPC2148) with V<sub>REF</sub> = 3.3 V:**

$$T(°C) = \frac{ADC_{value} \times 3.3}{1024 \times 0.01} = \frac{ADC_{value} \times 3.3}{10.24}$$

### 2.1.6 Seven Segment Display
- **Common-Cathode (CC)** vs **Common-Anode (CA):** Determines whether a '1' or '0' lights a segment.
- **Hex encoding table (Common-Cathode, 0–9):**

| Digit | a b c d e f g | Hex Code (gfedcba) |
|-------|--------------|--------------------|
| 0     | 1 1 1 1 1 1 0 | **0x3F** |
| 1     | 0 1 1 0 0 0 0 | **0x06** |
| 2     | 1 1 0 1 1 0 1 | **0x5B** |
| 3     | 1 1 1 1 0 0 1 | **0x4F** |
| 4     | 0 1 1 0 0 1 1 | **0x66** |
| 5     | 1 0 1 1 0 1 1 | **0x6D** |
| 6     | 1 0 1 1 1 1 1 | **0x7D** |
| 7     | 1 1 1 0 0 0 0 | **0x07** |
| 8     | 1 1 1 1 1 1 1 | **0x7F** |
| 9     | 1 1 1 1 0 1 1 | **0x6F** |

- **Multiplexed display** uses a shared data bus with separate digit-select lines, refreshed at **> 100 Hz** to appear continuous.

---

## 2.2 KTU High-Yield Formula Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Formula | Units | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| LED Series Resistor | $R = \frac{V_{CC} - V_F}{I_F}$ | Ω | Use $I_F \leq 10$ mA for 8051 safety |
| PWM Average Voltage | $V_{avg} = D \cdot V_{supply}$ | V | $D = t_{ON} / T$ |
| PWM Duty Cycle (%) | $D_{\%} = \frac{t_{ON}}{T} \times 100$ | % | Range 0–100 % |
| Stepper Step Angle | $\theta_{step} = \frac{360°}{N}$ | degrees | N = total steps/rev |
| LM35 Voltage | $V_{out} = 0.01 \cdot T$ | V | T in °C |
| ADC Digital Value (8-bit) | $D = \frac{V_{in}}{V_{REF}} \times 256$ | integer | Range 0–255 |
| ADC Digital Value (10-bit) | $D = \frac{V_{in}}{V_{REF}} \times 1024$ | integer | Range 0–1023 |
| Temperature from 8-bit ADC | $T = \frac{D \times V_{REF}}{256 \times 0.01}$ | °C | 8051 typical |
| Temperature from 10-bit ADC | $T = \frac{D \times V_{REF}}{1024 \times 0.01}$ | °C | LPC2148 typical |
| Display Refresh Frequency | $f_{refresh} = \frac{1}{N_{digits} \times t_{ON,digit}}$ | Hz | N = number of digits |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Engineering Utility:** These formulas drive **automotive dashboards** (temperature + speed), **CNC machines** (stepper precision), **HVAC controllers** (LM35 feedback), and **industrial PLC panels** (seven-segment HMIs). Mastering them is non-negotiable for any embedded roles.

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->

# SECTION 3: Step-by-Step Derivations, Code Walkthroughs & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Sample Code 1 — LED Blinking (8051, Keil C)

```c
#include <reg51.h>

sbit LED = P1^0;        // LED connected to P1.0

void delay(unsigned int ms) {
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < ms; i++)
        for(j = 0; j < 1275; j++);   // 1 ms @ 11.0592 MHz
}

void main(void) {
    while(1) {
        LED = 0;        // Active-LOW: sink current to light LED
        delay(500);
        LED = 1;        // OFF
        delay(500);
    }
}
```

### Line-by-Line Analytical Walkthrough

| Line | Explanation |
|------|-------------|
| `#include <reg51.h>` | Brings in the **SFR (Special Function Register) declarations** for the standard 8051 — P0, P1, P2, P3, etc. |
| `sbit LED = P1^0;` | Defines a **bit-addressable alias** to pin 0 of Port 1. `sbit` is a Keil extension that maps to the underlying bit-addressable memory area (20h–2Fh). |
| `delay(500)` inner loop 1275 | **Derivation:** 1 machine cycle = 12 oscillator cycles. For $f_{OSC} = 11.0592$ MHz, machine cycle ≈ **1.085 µs**. To produce 1 ms delay we need ≈ 921 machine cycles; considering loop overhead (DJNZ, jump, etc.), ≈ **1275 iterations** is the empirical count for the 8051. |
| `LED = 0;` | Writes 0 to P1.0. In active-LOW wiring, this **sinks current** and lights the LED. |
| `while(1)` | **Infinite loop** — embedded systems run forever; there is no OS to return to. |

---

## 3.2 Sample Code 2 — Switch Interfacing with Debounce (8051)

```c
#include <reg51.h>

sbit SW  = P3^0;        // Switch on P3.0 (active LOW, pulled up)
sbit LED = P1^0;

void delay_ms(unsigned int ms) {
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < ms; i++)
        for(j = 0; j < 1275; j++);
}

void main(void) {
    SW  = 1;            // Make P3.0 input (write 1 to disable internal pull-down logic)
    LED = 1;
    while(1) {
        if(SW == 0) {               // Button pressed?
            delay_ms(20);            // Debounce
            if(SW == 0) {
                LED = ~LED;          // Toggle LED state
                while(SW == 0);      // Wait for release (avoid retrigger)
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Derivation of Debounce Time

Mechanical switches exhibit contact bounce for typically 5–20 ms. Sampling at the **midpoint** of this window is safest.

$$t_{debounce} \in [5\,\text{ms},\; 30\,\text{ms}]$$

A common, conservative engineering choice is **$t_{debounce} = 20$ ms** — long enough to ride out all bounces, short enough to feel responsive.

---

## 3.3 Sample Code 3 — DC Motor Speed Control with PWM (8051 + L293D)

```c
#include <reg51.h>

sbit IN1 = P2^0;        // Direction control pin 1
sbit IN2 = P2^1;        // Direction control pin 2
sbit EN  = P2^2;        // Enable / PWM input

void delay_ms(unsigned int ms) {
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < ms; i++)
        for(j = 0; j < 1275; j++);
}

void main(void) {
    IN1 = 1; IN2 = 0;            // Forward direction
    while(1) {
        EN = 1;
        delay_ms(20);            // ON for 20 ms  (PWM ON time)
        EN = 0;
        delay_ms(80);            // OFF for 80 ms (PWM OFF time)
                                  // Duty cycle = 20/(20+80) = 20%
    }
}
```

### PWM Duty Cycle Derivation

$$D = \frac{t_{ON}}{t_{ON} + t_{OFF}} = \frac{20}{20 + 80} = 0.20 = 20\%$$

For 8051 the practical PWM period for a DC motor is **1 ms to 25 ms** (i.e., frequency 40 Hz to 1 kHz). Outside this range, the motor either whines audibly (< 20 Hz) or loses torque (> 25 kHz due to coil inductance).

> [!TIP]
> **KTU Valuation Tip:** Writing the duty cycle derivation in the exam gets you a free mark. Examiners *love* seeing the math, not just the code.

---

## 3.4 Sample Code 4 — Stepper Motor Full-Step Rotation (8051, Unipolar)

```c
#include <reg51.h>

// Coil connections
sbit COIL_A = P1^0;
sbit COIL_B = P1^1;
sbit COIL_C = P1^2;
sbit COIL_D = P1^3;

void delay_ms(unsigned int ms) {
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < ms; i++)
        for(j = 0; j < 1275; j++);
}

void rotate_CW(unsigned int steps) {
    unsigned char seq[4] = {0x01, 0x02, 0x04, 0x08};  // A, B, C, D
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < steps; i++) {
        for(j = 0; j < 4; j++) {
            P1 = seq[j];
            delay_ms(10);            // 10 ms per step → smooth rotation
        }
    }
}

void main(void) {
    while(1) {
        rotate_CW(200);              // 200 steps = 1 full revolution
    }
}
```

### Step Angle Derivation

For a 200-step/revolution motor:

$$\theta_{step} = \frac{360°}{200} = 1.8° \text{ per full step}$$

For half-step mode (8-step sequence), the same motor has:

$$\theta_{half} = \frac{360°}{400} = 0.9° \text{ per half step}$$

To rotate a shaft by **90°** at full-step:

$$N = \frac{90°}{1.8°/\text{step}} = 50 \text{ steps}$$

---

## 3.5 Sample Code 5 — Temperature Monitoring with LM35 (8051 + ADC0804)

```c
#include <reg51.h>

#define ADC_DATA P0        // ADC0804 data bus connected to P0
sbit ADC_RD  = P3^0;       // Read strobe
sbit ADC_WR  = P3^1;       // Write / Start-of-Conversion
sbit ADC_INTR = P3^2;      // End-of-Conversion (active LOW)

void delay_ms(unsigned int ms) {
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < ms; i++)
        for(j = 0; j < 1275; j++);
}

unsigned char read_adc(void) {
    unsigned char value;
    ADC_WR = 0;            // Start conversion
    delay_ms(1);
    ADC_WR = 1;
    while(ADC_INTR == 1);  // Wait for EOC
    ADC_RD = 0;            // Latch output
    value  = ADC_DATA;     // Read 8-bit value
    ADC_RD = 1;
    return value;
}

void main(void) {
    unsigned char adc_val;
    float temperature;
    P0 = 0xFF;             // Configure P0 as input
    while(1) {
        adc_val     = read_adc();
        temperature = (adc_val * 5.0) / 2.56;   // 5 V ref, 8-bit
        // Display on LCD / UART (omitted for brevity)
        delay_ms(500);
    }
}
```

### Derivation of Temperature Equation

**Step 1 — ADC digital output:**

$$D = \frac{V_{in}}{V_{REF}} \times 2^{n}$$

For 8-bit ADC ($n = 8$) and $V_{REF} = 5$ V:

$$D = \frac{V_{in}}{5} \times 256$$

**Step 2 — Solve for $V_{in}$:**

$$V_{in} = \frac{D \times 5}{256}$$

**Step 3 — LM35 relationship:**

$$V_{in} = 0.01 \times T \quad \Rightarrow \quad T = \frac{V_{in}}{0.01} = 100 \cdot V_{in}$$

**Step 4 — Combine:**

$$T = 100 \times \frac{D \times 5}{256} = \frac{D \times 500}{256} = \frac{D \times 5}{2.56}$$

This is the exact formula used in the code: `temperature = (adc_val * 5.0) / 2.56;`

### Worked Example Calculation

Suppose ADC returns $D = 77$ (decimal). Then:

$$T = \frac{77 \times 5}{2.56} = \frac{385}{2.56} = 150.39\,°C$$

This corresponds to $V_{in} = 1.504$ V, which matches $150.4\,°C \times 10$ mV/°C = **1.504 V**. ✔

---

## 3.6 Sample Code 6 — Seven Segment Display (Multiplexed, 4-Digit)

```c
#include <reg51.h>

// Segment data bus (active HIGH: 1 = segment ON)
#define SEG_DATA P0

// Digit select lines (transistor drivers)
sbit D1 = P2^0;
sbit D2 = P2^1;
sbit D3 = P2^2;
sbit D4 = P2^3;

// Hex codes for digits 0–9 (common-cathode)
unsigned char seg_code[10] = {
    0x3F, 0x06, 0x5B, 0x4F, 0x66,
    0x6D, 0x7D, 0x07, 0x7F, 0x6F
};

void delay_ms(unsigned int ms) {
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < ms; i++)
        for(j = 0; j < 1275; j++);
}

void display_digit(unsigned char pos, unsigned char val) {
    // Turn OFF all digits first (avoid ghosting)
    D1 = D2 = D3 = D4 = 1;
    switch(pos) {
        case 0: D1 = 0; break;
        case 1: D2 = 0; break;
        case 2: D3 = 0; break;
        case 3: D4 = 0; break;
    }
    SEG_DATA = seg_code[val];
    delay_ms(5);
}

void main(void) {
    unsigned char value = 27;        // Display "0027"
    unsigned char d0, d1, d2, d3;
    d0 = value % 10;
    d1 = (value / 10) % 10;
    d2 = (value / 100) % 10;
    d3 = 0;
    while(1) {
        display_digit(0, d0);
        display_digit(1, d1);
        display_digit(2, d2);
        display_digit(3, d3);
    }
}
```

### Multiplexing Refresh Rate Derivation

For 4 digits, each lit for $t_{ON} = 5$ ms:

$$T_{refresh} = 4 \times 5\,\text{ms} = 20\,\text{ms}$$

$$f_{refresh} = \frac{1}{20\,\text{ms}} = 50\,\text{Hz}$$

> [!WARNING]
> A refresh rate of **50 Hz** is *just* above the human flicker threshold (≈ 50–60 Hz in peripheral vision). For robust KTU board demos, use **$t_{ON} = 2$ ms** (i.e., 125 Hz overall) to avoid visible flicker under fluorescent lab lighting.

---

## 3.7 Analytical Matrix: Peripherals vs Configuration Registers (8051)

| Peripheral | 8051 SFR | Reset Value | Direction Setting | Use Case |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| **Port 0** | P0 | 0xFF | Must be pulled-up externally | Address/Data bus (external memory) |
| **Port 1** | P1 | 0xFF | Quasi-bidirectional | General I/O (LEDs, switches) |
| **Port 2** | P2 | 0xFF | Quasi-bidirectional | Higher address bus |
| **Port 3** | P3 | 0xFF | Alternate functions: RXD, TXD, INT0, INT1, T0, T1, WR, RD | Special functions |
| **Timer 0** | TMOD, TH0, TL0, TCON | 0x00 | Mode 0, 1, 2, 3 | Delay generation, baud clock |
| **ADC0804** | External chip, control via P3 pins | — | — | LM35 analog input |
| **L293D** | External H-bridge, control via P2 | — | — | DC motor / stepper driver |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Trap Question:** Port 0 of 8051 is an **open-drain** port — it cannot source current. You *must* connect external pull-up resistors (typically **10 kΩ**) if you want to read a HIGH. This is the #1 reason student boards malfunction.

