## 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks — Module Internal Choice)

### **Question A (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam – June 2024, Module 4]**

**(a)** Design and write an 8051 C program to interface a **DC motor with the L293D driver**. The motor should rotate clockwise for 5 seconds, stop for 2 seconds, then rotate anticlockwise for 5 seconds. Use PWM at 50 % duty cycle for both directions. Explain the register configurations used. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** With a neat circuit diagram, explain how **LM35 temperature sensor** is interfaced to 8051 through **ADC0804**. Write the C program to read the temperature and display it on the serial port at 9600 baud (11.0592 MHz crystal). The temperature should be displayed as integer °C. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution — (a) [7 marks]

**Hardware Connections (2 marks):**
- P2.0 → IN1, P2.1 → IN2, P2.2 → EN1 (PWM)
- L293D OUT1/OUT2 → DC Motor terminals
- L293D Vcc2 (pin 8) → +12 V (motor supply)
- L293D Vcc1 (pin 16) → +5 V (logic supply)
- 8051 P1.0 → Status LED (optional)

**C Program (4 marks):**
```c
#include <reg51.h>

sbit IN1 = P2^0;
sbit IN2 = P2^1;
sbit EN  = P2^2;

void delay_ms(unsigned int ms) {
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < ms; i++)
        for(j = 0; j < 1275; j++);
}

void pwm_50(unsigned int total_ms) {
    unsigned int t = total_ms / 2;
    while(total_ms > 0) {
        EN = 1;  delay_ms(t);   // 50% ON
        EN = 0;  delay_ms(t);   // 50% OFF
        total_ms -= 2*t;
    }
}

void main(void) {
    while(1) {
        IN1 = 1; IN2 = 0;                 // CW
        pwm_50(5000);
        EN = 0; delay_ms(2000);            // Stop 2 s
        IN1 = 0; IN2 = 1;                 // CCW
        pwm_50(5000);
        EN = 0; delay_ms(2000);
    }
}
```

**Register Configuration Note (1 mark):**
The 8051 ports are reset to **0xFF** (input-ready quasi-bidirectional). No explicit `PX = 0xFF` initialization is required for the bit-wise `sbit` operations. The PWM frequency is determined by the delay: $T_{PWM} = 2t$ where $t = 25$ ms here → $f_{PWM} = 20$ Hz (within audible range but acceptable for slow DC motor).

