### **Question B (14 Marks) — [KTU University Exam – June 2024, Module 4, Alternative]**

**(a)** With a neat schematic, explain the **interfacing of a 4-digit common-cathode seven segment display** to 8051 using **multiplexing**. Write the C program to display a 4-digit number "1234" continuously, refreshing at a rate fast enough to avoid flicker. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write an 8051 C program to control a **unipolar stepper motor** to rotate in clockwise direction for **180°**, then anticlockwise for **90°**, and then stop. Assume a **1.8° step angle** motor. Explain the excitation sequence used. **(7 marks)**

#### Model Solution — (a) [7 marks]

**Multiplexed Connection (2 marks):**
- All 4 digits' segment lines (a–g + dp) are tied together to **P0.0–P0.6**.
- Each digit's **common cathode** is driven by an NPN transistor (e.g., BC547) controlled by P2.0–P2.3.
- A single current-limiting resistor (≈ 220 Ω) is placed on each segment line (or a single resistor on the common pin in some designs).

**C Program (4 marks):**
```c
#include <reg51.h>

#define SEG P0
sbit D1 = P2^0;
sbit D2 = P2^1;
sbit D3 = P2^2;
sbit D4 = P2^3;

unsigned char seg_code[10] = {
    0x3F, 0x06, 0x5B, 0x4F, 0x66,
    0x6D, 0x7D, 0x07, 0x7F, 0x6F
};

void delay_ms(unsigned int ms) {
    unsigned int i, j;
    for(i = 0; i < ms; i++)
        for(j = 0; j < 1275; j++);
}

void show(unsigned char pos, unsigned char d) {
    D1 = D2 = D3 = D4 = 1;     // Blank all
    switch(pos) {
        case 0: D1 = 0; break;
        case 1: D2 = 0; break;
        case 2: D3 = 0; break;
        case 3: D4 = 0; break;
    }
    SEG = seg_code[d];
    delay_ms(2);               // 2 ms per digit → 125 Hz overall
}

void main(void) {
    unsigned char d0=4, d1=3, d2=2, d3=1;
    while(1) {
        show(3, d3);  show(2, d2);
        show(1, d1);  show(0, d0);
    }
}
```

**Refresh Frequency Calculation (1 mark):**
$$f_{refresh} = \frac{1}{4 \times 2\,\text{ms}} = 125\,\text{Hz}$$
This is well above the human flicker fusion threshold (~60 Hz), ensuring a stable display.

